@@@ [u' \xa0 Britney Spears took her hit song "Oops I Did It Again" from Louis Armstrong.\n', u'\n', u'\n\n', u'\n\n', u'\n', u'\n', u' ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u' \xa0 Trumpeter Louis Armstrong was one of the most renowned musicians of the 20th century, and his influence is still apparent in today\'s music. In fact, according to an Internet rumor, the 2000 Britney Spears hit song "Oops I Did It Again" was actually a cover of a song first recorded by Satchmo himself:\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nBut there is no truth to this rumor. Louis Armstrong neither wrote nor recorded "Oops I Did It Again." \n', u'\nThe Satchmo imitation music heard in the above-displayed video was created by the ', u' web site Super Master Piece in 2005 and presented as a 1932 recording made by Armstrong and released on the Decca label: \n', u' \n', u'\n', u'\n', u"\n\nDespite this interesting back story, the web site didn't hide the fact that this rendition was fabricated. The music was originally published with a ", u' noting its origins as a parody and crediting the real musicians:\n\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nNeither Louis Armstrong nor Britney Spears had a hand in writing "Oops I Did It Again." That credit goes to Swedish music producers Rami Yacoub and Max Martin. \n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u' \xa0 2 June 2015\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n'] @@@
