@@@ [u' \xa0 Members of the Congressional Prayer Caucus sent President Obama a letter correcting his reference to ', u' as the U.S. national motto.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 During a speech he delivered at the University of Indonesia in Jakarta on ', u' 2010, President Obama said: "I believe that the history of both America and Indonesia should give us hope. It is a story written into our national mottos. In the United States, our motto is ', u' ', u' of many, one.  Our nations show that hundreds of millions who hold different beliefs can be united in freedom under one flag."\r\n', u'\r\nIn 1782, the U.S. Continental Congress proposed the use of the Latin phrase ', u' (commonly translated as "out of many, one" or "one from many") on the ', u" of the United States as a reference to the original thirteen American colonies' having joined together as a single united entity.  The phrase is still a component of the Seal of the United States and has appeared on U.S. coinage since 1795.  \r\n\r\n", u'\r\n\r\nHowever, although ', u' was long considered the ', u' national motto of the United States, it was never officially established as such by legislation.   The only legislatively established national motto the United States has ever had is "In God We Trust," a phrase which first appeared on ', u' in 1864 (and is now a part of ', u' ', u' and coinage) and which was adopted as the official U.S. national motto through a law passed by Congress in 1956.\r\n', u'\r\nOn 6 December 2010, forty-two members (forty-one Republicans and one Democrat) of the ', u', an organization founded and ', u' by Congressman ', u' ', u' of Virginia, sent a ', u' to President Obama to correct his reference to  ', u' as the U.S. national motto:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n(The fourth and final stanza of the U.S. national anthem, ', u', contains the line: "And this be our motto: \'In God is our trust\'.)\r\n', u'\r\nOther modern presidents have made reference to ', u' as the U.S. motto with little or no comment, such as President Ronald Reagan, who, in an ', u' to the National Forum on Excellence in Education in 1983, said: "The motto of the United States is ', u' from many, one. Well, more than any other institution, our schools built that one from the many."\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 13 January 2011\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
