@@@ [u' \xa0  The outcome of Washington Redskins home football games has correctly predicted the winner of every ', u' election since 1936.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 Our desire to understand and assert some control over the world around us is often manifested by our attempts to find predictive signs that enable us to prognosticate ', u' when there is no seeming connection between predictor and event.  Sometimes one natural phenomenon supposedly forecasts another, as in the belief that a \r\n\r\n', u' \r\n\r\n', u"'s seeing his shadow on ", u" portends another six weeks of winter.  In other instances the linkage is between affairs of mankind, as in the superstition that the winner of football's ", u" augurs that year's stock market performance (or vice-versa).\r\n", u'\r\nOne item of this ilk which gained currency in 2004 maintained that the results of the last game played ', u" by the NFL's Redskins (a football team based in the national capital, Washington, D.C.) before a ", u' election foretold the winner of that contest.  If the Redskins won their last home game before the election, the party that occupied the White House continued to hold it; if the Redskins lost that last home game, the challenger from the out-of-office party unseated the incumbent party.  And up until that 2004 election, the Redskins indicator had a rather remarkable record: Since 1936, the earliest \r\n\r\n', u"\r\n\r\npresidential election year in which the current Redskins franchise played under that team name, the team's results had currently predicted the outcome of ", u' presidential contests.  \r\n', u"\r\nReality finally trumped coincidence in 2004, however: Despite the Green Bay Packers' ", u' ', u" of the Redskins at the latter's home field on ", u', presaging a victory for Democratic challenger John Kerry in upcoming the presidential election, two days later incumbent President ', u' Bus