@@@ [u" \xa0 Quip about agitators answers Rev. Jesse Jackson's protest about color of washing machines.\r\n", u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u" \xa0 In the wake of 2005's Hurricane Katrina and the maelstrom of accusations and fingerpointing slow response to that disaster engendered, this ancient piece about the ", u' Jackson was revived and circulated anew. In 1994 it made the rounds in the form of an exchange between Jesse Jackson and President George H.W. Bush:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThis well-traveled anecdote is an amusing study in double meanings: "agitator" serves to describe both a political troublemaker and the washing machine part that churns water. Yet at a deeper level, the witticism is intended not as humor but as a denigration\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nof a type of political activism for which the ', u' serves as a ', u' is perceived by many not as a true civil rights crusader in the mold of ', u' Luther ', u' or Nelson Mandela, but as a manipulative politician who manufactures and exploits racial controversy for his own political ends.  Thus the joke labels him an "agitator" within the framework of a story about a harebrained protest over the color of household appliances to represent the perception of ', u' as someone primarily concerned not with advancing the cause of civil rights, but with stirring up racial discord for the sake of generating publicity and enhancing his own political standing.\r\n', u'\r\nWhile this chronicle of a protest over the color of washing machines is fiction, it is worth noting the quip that forms the basis of it has been employed in real life by at least one African American office seeker. In 1999 during his mayoral bid in Biddeford, Maine, Rory Holland referred to himself as a "little black agitator in a white washing machine."\r\n', u'\r\nBarbara "he washed out in the election" Mikkelson\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 3 October 2005\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\xa0\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n'] @@@
