@@@ [u" \xa0 E-mail offers an Oakland high school student's Ebonics competition-winning translations of rap lyrics.\r\n", u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u" \xa0 It's not uncommon for us to see urban legends transformed into jokes, or jokes rendered as urban legends.  (The basic difference is that urban legends are told as true occurrences, while \r\n\r\n", u"\r\n\r\njokes are understood to be humorous but fictional anecdotes.)  The latter process doesn't generally result in much improvement, however ", u' rarely is the humor of a joke enhanced by prefacing it with a "This is a true story!" tag.\r\n', u'\r\nSo, we\'re at a loss to know why someone saw fit to tack a spurious claim about an "Oakland high school Ebonics competition" onto this waggish piece offering translations of rap lyrics into a more standard form of English.  The version quoted above has been bouncing around the Internet since 1997, and ', u" we can't be sure that he was the originator of all the entries ", u' sounds a lot like a routine comedian ', u' typically performs in his stand-up shows, during which he offers "translations of rap lyrics for white people."  His performance of such a routine is captured in his most recent ', u' "\'I\'m Swiss\' and Other Treasonable Statements," currently airing on HBO.\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 4 August 2005\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\xa0\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n'] @@@
