@@@ [u' \xa0 The state of Montana passed a law nullifying federal authority to regulate guns in that state.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 In April 2009, the state of Montana ', u' the ', u', legislation stating that "a personal firearm, a firearm accessory, or ammunition that is manufactured commercially or privately in Montana and that remains within the borders of Montana is not subject to federal law or federal regulation, including registration, under the authority of congress to regulate interstate commerce," essentially a declaration that the ', u' government has no authority to regulate any firearms manufactured, sold, and owned within the state of Montana.  \r\n', u'\r\nMontana has said, in effect, that the authority of Congress to regulate interstate commerce does not give Congress the authority to regulate firearms in Montana that have not been involved in any form of interstate commerce.  However, state legislatures do not have the authority to interpret or nullify ', u' Court decisions regarding federal constitutional powers, so any attempt by Montana to enforce the Firearms Freedom Act would likely be struck down by the ', u' Court as unconstitutional. \r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 9 May 2009\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
