@@@ [u' \xa0 The U.S. government unfairly excluded Hawker Beechcraft from bidding to supply military aircraft for Afghanistan.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0  On 30 December 2011, the U.S. Department of Defense announced that it had awarded a ', u' contract to Sierra Nevada Corp. (SNC) for ', u" air-support/single-engine turboprop aircraft that will serve as both trainers and ground-attack planes for Afghanistan's air force.  Wichita-based aircraft manufacturer Hawker Beechcraft (HBDC) had hoped that their ", u' aircraft, an armed version of their ', u' trainer which is currently used by the U.S. military, would be chosen for the contract, but the U.S. Air Force (USAF) excluded the ', u' from the running, leaving the ', u' Super Tucano built by Sierra Nevada Corp. in partnership with Brazil-based Embraer as the lone eligible supplier.\r\n', u'\r\nHawker Beechcraft Corp. has since filed suit against the U.S. government over the exclusion, maintaining that the Air Force had not provided them with sufficient detail about the reasons behind their exclusion and that Embraer had been unfairly favored:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThe Air Force maintains that the process was fair, that Hawker Beechcraft was excluded because "multiple deficiencies and significant weaknesses found in HBDC\'s proposal make it technically unacceptable and results in unacceptable mission capability risk," and that the company failed to ', u' to its notice of exclusion in time to request a debriefing or file a protest:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nIt is not possible at this point to definitively determine why the USAF excluded Hawker Beechcraft from the Light Aircraft Support (LAS) bidding, as ongoing litigation prevents the Air Force from releasing information regarding the competition, but according to industry ', u" the primary issue behind Hawker Beechcraft's disqualification was that the LAS contract called for a non-developmental, production-ready aircraft, and Hawker Beechcraft's ", u' was still a developmental aircraft.  \r\n', u"\r\nAccording to SNC's own ", u' on the issue:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nIn February 2012, the Air Force announced it was canceling the contract with Sierra Nevada Corp. pending an investigation of the award:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThe awarding of the Air Force contract to a partner of Brazil-based Embraer did not necessarily mean that all the jobs connected with the contract would be sent overseas, as Embraer said that its partner, Nevada-based Sierra Nevada Corp., would build the turboprops in Jacksonville, Florida, if it won the contract:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nDespite the claim made in the example text reproduced above that the subject of Hawker Beechcraft\'s exclusion was "completely ignored by the mainstream media," it has in fact received ', u' news coverage in a variety of media sources, including at least five of the nine highest-circulation newspapers in the U.S. (', u', ', u', the San Jose ', u', the ', u', and the ', u').\r\n', u'\r\nAlso, we found no evidence to support the claim that "If this contract goes to Embraer it will be a huge pay off to another George Soros company,"  as we turned up no information indicating that George Soros holds an ownership stake in Embraer.  The closest connection we found between George Soros and Embraer seems to be that the former is one of the leading ', u" in China's Hainan Airlines Group (HNA), and HNA bought ", u' jets from Harbin Embraer, a partnership between Embraer and the Harbin Aircraft Manufacturing Corporation of Harbin, China. However, that connection makes Soros a customer of Embraer, not an owner, and therefore does not put him in a position to profit from the awarding of an Air Force contact to Embraer.\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 5 March 2012\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
