@@@ [u' \xa0  Article contrasts compensation paid to families of ', u' victims with benefits paid to families of U.S. military personnel killed on active duty.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 The above-referenced Rush Limbaugh piece from March 2002 contrasts the compensation paid to families of ', u' victims with benefits paid to families of ', u' personnel killed on active duty.  Although most of the figures cited in the article were accurate at the time it was written, subsequent changes have made much of the original article outdated.\r\n', u'\r\nFamily members of September 11 victims (which include those killed at the World Trade Centers, the Pentagon, and the Shanksville, Pennsylvania, crash site) could apply to receive ', u' from the Victim Compensation Fund (VCF) established by the federal government.  The (non-taxable) compensation ', u' included $250,000 (plus an additional $100,000 for the spouse and each dependent of the victim) in non-economic losses, plus additional compensation for economic loss determined by ', u" such as the victim's age and income level.  As of April 2004, more than ", u' in compensation had been ', u' out, with the families of deceased victims receiving an average of ', u' each.\r\n', u"\r\nIn contrast, back in 2002 the figures listed on the military's ", u' chart regarding benefits provided to the families of service members who died or were killed on active duty were paltry by comparison:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nSince then, however, the amount of the ', u' has been increased to a non-taxable $100,000 (retroactive to ', u' 2001), and the ', u' amounts have been raised to an $1,154 monthly annuity plus an additional $286 monthly allowance for each dependent child (effective ', u' 2008 for veterans who died on or after ', u' 1993).\r\n', u"\r\nAlso, the original piece didn't mention that military personnel are automatically insured (unless they decline the coverage) under the Servicemembers' Group Life \r\n\r\n", u'\r\n\r\nInsurance (', u') program, which at the time paid a maximum benefit of $250,000 to the families of servicemen killed while on active ', u' same as the base amount paid through the VCF to the families of civilians killed in the ', u' terrorist attacks.  The maximum SGLI benefit has since been increased to $400,000.  \r\n', u'\r\nWe note that service members have to pay ', u' for SGLI (currently $27 per month for the maximum coverage), and that many of the civilians killed in the 9/11 terrorist attacks also had life insurance policies which paid benefits to their surviving family members.\r\n', u'\r\nThis piece has also been circulated with a coda that looks like it was tacked on by someone else, possibly as a commentary on the article which has now mistakenly been assumed to be a part of the original article itself:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThe claim that Congressmen can receive lavish pensions after serving only a single term in Congress (eventually totaling into the millions of dollars) and that they neither pay into nor receive benefits from the Social Security fund is misinformation already covered in a separate ', u' on this site.  (As of 2007, the average annuity for retired members of Congress was between about $36,000 and $63,000.) \r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 7 February 2010\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
@@@ [u" \xa0 A display at the National World War II Memorial excised the words 'So help us God' from a speech by President Roosevelt.\r\n\r\n", u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 On 29 May 2004, as part of the annual ', u" Day observances honoring those who died in our nation's service, the long-awaited ", u' in \r\nWashington, D.C., was formally dedicated.  (The memorial had opened for public viewing a month prior to its official dedication ceremonies.)\r\n', u'\r\nTo \r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nmost Americans ', u' those who lived through World ', u'  ', u' words associated with that conflict are more familiar or more stirring than those delivered by President ', u' Roosevelt as he stood before Congress on ', u' 1941, the day after the surprise attack by Japanese forces on the ', u' base at Pearl Harbor in Hawaii, and asked for a declaration of war against Japan.  Accordingly, no American memorial to World ', u" would be complete without a reproduction of at least a portion of President Roosevelt's memorable speech.\r\n", u'\r\nThe message quoted above (which looks to be a reworking of an item originally ', u' in the ', u' on ', u" 2004) claims that an excerpt from FDR's ", u" 1941 speech which is inscribed on the side of the memorial dedicated to the war in the Pacific deliberately excised the words 'so help us God,' as uttered by President Roosevelt that day, because 'We're not supposed to say things like that now.' Ironically, this claim is apparently based on some anonymous person's flawed recollection, the very sort of tampering with memory that the message warns us against.\r\n", u"\r\nHere is the complete text of President Roosevelt's ", u' 1941 address to Congress:\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u"\r\nOut of that twenty-four sentence speech, only a single sentence (the one highlighted in red above), prefaced by Roosevelt's famous opening words, is inscribed on the National World "