id snaps: Each shared an identical background and labeling, and all were obviously compiled representations of school lunch ', u" from countries outside the United States. It's likely students in all the countries named could capture less photogenic daily fare actually served in their cafeterias if asked.\r\n", u'\r\nThe ', u' blog post not only fell for the misleadingly swapped-in photo, but it also elided a crucial portion of the ', u' article that showed the piece did not claim British school lunches were superior to American versions:\r\n\r\n', u"\r\n\r\nMoreover, no initiatives promoted by Michelle Obama (whose focus on nutrition is both well known and widely criticized) even remotely inspired the unpleasantries seen in some of the circulating photos of American cafeteria lunches. The First Lady's school lunch initiatives have hinged on providing ", u', daily portions of fruits and vegetables, and reduction of trans fats [', u'] in cafeteria foods. The standards ', u' sought to incorporate are precisely the same ones illustrated in the photographs of foods from other countries: fresh vegetables, complex carbohydrates, and other high-quality ingredients.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 26 February 2015\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
