@@@ [u' \xa0 Students at Liberty University faced a $10 fine if they missed a Ted Cruz speech.\n', u'\n', u'\n\n', u'\n\n', u'\n', u'\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\n', u' \xa0  On ', u' 2015, Senator Ted Cruz announced his intent to pursue the Republican nomination for the 2016 presidential race. Cruz, the first major candidate to make such an announcement, did so during a speech at Liberty University in Lynchburg, Virginia.', u'\n\n', u"\n\nFollowing Cruz's ", u" 2015 speech, reports began circulating on the Internet claiming that students at Liberty University were obliged to attend the event under the threat of a $10 fine. On the day of Cruz's speech, the website ", u" published an article about the unusually strict attendance requirements for certain events at Liberty University, including the one at which CRuz's announcement was made. The site interviewed students (mainly supporters of Rand Paul, a potential challenger to Cruz) who felt that their conscripted attendance gave an inaccurate impression of widespread endorsement by the student body:\n\n", u"\n\nMany individuals not affiliated with Liberty University took the claims to mean that students were ordered to pay a fine if they opted out of attending Cruz's speech. While that was technically true to a degree, it wasn't quite accurate in the broader context of the school's rules and regulations.", u"\n\nSince well before Ted Cruz announced his 2016 presidential candidacy, Liberty University has maintained a policy mandating student attendance for several weekly convocation events. Per the school's current Student Appeals Court Handbook [", u'], an unauthorized absence from required convocation events (whether or not Ted Cruz is involved) constitutes an infraction for which a ', u' is clearly articulated. Other infractions at that level include dress code violations, breaking curfew while residing on campus, and "horseplay."', u"\n\nIn response to the rumors about Cruz's appearance at Liberty University and fines, President Jerry Falwell clarified the purpose of convocation in a ", u' which explained that the senator was one of many figures invited to appear at such events throughout the school year: \n\n', u"\n\nWhile students at Liberty University were subject to fines for missing the convocation event at which Ted Cruz announced his candidacy, that was true for all events of that description at the institution (and students are required to attend several each week). Some students (particularly those who favored different candidates) objected to what they deemed an implied endorsement of Cruz, but the appearance in question was no different from others involving guest speakers at the university. Not only was Cruz's speech not unique in terms of mandatory attendance and fines, but the candidate was only one of many politicians to appear at Liberty University's regular convocation events. \n", u'\n', u' \xa0 25 March 2015\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n'] @@@
@@@ [u' \xa0 Ted Cruz is ineligible to serve as President of the United States because he was born in Canada.\n', u'\n', u'\n\n', u'\n\n', u'\n', u'\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\n', u' \xa0  Well before Texas senator Ted Cruz officially announced his candidacy for the 2016 Republican presidential nomination on ', u' 2015, pundits had been questioning his eligibility to hold the office he sought\n\n', u"\n\ndue to the fact that he was born in Canada rather than in the United States.  Moreover, Cruz's father was a native-born Cuban who did not obtain U.S. citizenship until long after the birth of his son.\n", u'\nOne of the issues of controvery was that ', u' ', u' of the ', u' states "No person except a natural born citizen shall be eligible to the office of President" but doesn\'t precisely define what the term "natural born citizen" means:\n\n', u'\n\n\nThe term "natural born citizen" has generally been interpreted to refer to any person who qualified for U.S. citizenship by virtue of the circumstances of his birth, and in that regard Ted Cruz meets the requirement for "natural born citizen" even though he was born outside the U.S. and had a ', u' parent.  The relevant ', u' that defines who "shall be nationals and citizens of the United States at birth" includes the following condition:\n\n', u"\n\nSince Ted Cruz's mother, the former Eleanor Elizabeth Wilson, was a U.S. citizen born in Wilmington, Delaware, who had lived for at least a decade in the United States, he qualified for U.S. citizenship at birth under this condition.  \n", u'\nIn an article entitled "Is Ted Cruz a natural-born citizen eligible to serve as president?" ', u' by the ', u' on ', u' 2013, scholar Sarah Helene Duggin explained that while the Supreme Court has never ruled on the precise meaning of a "natural born citizen," previous presidential bids by foreign-born candidates such as John McCain and George Romney have established legal precedents for Cruz to run in 2016. Duggin also ', u' to the Naturalization Act of 1790, which states that "children of citizens of the United States, that may be born beyond the sea, or out of the limits of the United States, shall be considered as natural-born citizens":\n\n', u'\n\nThe Harvard Law Review ', u' with Duggin\'s assessment, writing that there was "no question" about Cruz\'s eligibility:\n\n', u'\n\nThe Congressional Research Service also weighed in on the ', u" when questions were raised about President Obama's birth certificate in 2009:\n\n", u'\n\nAnother issue was that since Ted Cruz was born in Calgary, Alberta, he also qualified for Canadian citizenship at birth.  Although nothing in the ', u' specifically prohibits a ', u' from holding dual citizenship, such a situation could create a politically contentious situation regarding a President with "divided loyalties" even if the law did allow it.  \n', u'\nHowever, there is a difference between merely being ', u' for citizenship in a second country and actually ', u' such citizenship.  Many ', u' have been born under circumstances that made them eligible for citizenship in another country as well, but they never took any action to actually claim that second citizenship, such as residing in the second country as an adult, working for its government, serving in its military, voting in its elections, applying for a passport, or the like.  Cruz apparently never made any overt attempt to claim Canadian citizenship:\n\n', u'\n\nNonetheless, both U.S. and Canadian authorities opined that Cruz was in fact a dual U.S.-Canadian citizen:\n\n', u'\n\nAll of that is now moot, however, because in 2013 Ted Cruz took steps to formally renounce any claim to Canadian citizenship:\n\n', u'\n\nThat process of renunciation was accomplished by May of 2014:\n\n', u'\n\nIn May of 2014 the Government of Canada issued a ', u" acknowledging Ted Cruz's renunciation of Canadian citizenship as of ", u' 2014.\n', u'\n', u' \xa0 23 March 2015\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n'] @@@
