@@@ [u" \xa0 Mitt Romney assisted in the search for his business partner's missing daughter.\r\n", u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 On 6 July 1996, Melissa Gay, the 14-year-old daughter of investment firm Bain Capital managing director Robert Gay, took a train from her home in Connecticut to ', u' City and failed to return home.  According to contemporaneous news reports, Melissa had met up with two young men she knew, gone with them to a rave party on Randalls Island, taken several doses of Ecstasy, and then was last seen at a party in a park beneath the Whitestone Bridge in the Bronx.  When Melissa hadn\'t come home by the following morning, her parents said, "That\'s when we knew something was not right"; they called all her friends in an effort to locate her and then called the police.\r\n', u"\r\nIn the days following Melissa's disappearance, Bain Capital \u2014 whose partners and founders included Mitt Romney \u2014 all but shut down as the firm mobilized its resources to assist in the efforts to find Robert Gay's daughter.  As the ", u' Times reported at the time:\r\n\r\n', u"\r\n\r\nNews accounts of the time made mention of the role Mitt Romney and other partners at Bain Capital played in helping to find their managing director's daughter.  The ", u', for example, reported that:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nMelissa was eventually found six days after she disappeared due to a tip obtained when a teenaged boy who saw one of the televised "Help us find Melissa" appeals called 911:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nIn a followup article several months later, the ', u" noted that Bain Capital's partners had selected their search efforts on Melissa's behalf as their top accomplishment of 1996:\r\n\r\n", u'\r\n\r\nIn a 2002 ', u' article, Robert Gay credited Mitt Romney with being instrumental in organizing the search for his daughter:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nA 2007 New Hampshire campaign ', u' for  Mitt Romn