@@@ [u' \xa0 Article demonstrates how to eliminate U.S. oil imports from Middle Eastern countries.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u" \xa0 This item about a scheme for Americans to avoid purchasing gasoline produced from imported oil has been circulating in various forms since 2002 and has undergone many revisions.  It is now confusing mishmash that can't decide whether it's a plan for informing consumers where to buy gasoline produced in the United States, how to avoid oil companies that import crude from Saudi Arabia, how to avoid oil companies that import crude from the Middle East, or how to avoid oil companies that import crude from OPEC countries (many of which are not Middle Eastern).  The most important fact to note about this item is that it contained many gross statistical errors and exhibited a severely flawed grasp of oil industry economics at the time it was originally written, and it has only become worse over time.\r\n", u"\r\nOne of the misleading messages implicit in this text is the suggestion that most of the USA's crude oil is imported from the Middle East.  It isn't.  According to recent ", u' regarding crude oil imports, in ', u" only 25% of the USA's crude oil imports came from countries classified by the ", u' of Energy (DOE) as Persian Gulf exporters (i.e., Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, Bahrain).  A list of the top six countries supplying crude oil to the USA in January 2012 (by percentage of total USA imports) includes only a single Middle Eastern country:\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\nMoving along, we find that many of the statistics offered in the piece quoted above are erroneous or outdated:\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThis information is quite outdated.  In January 2012 the top five ', u' importing oil from the Persian Gulf were as follows:\r\n', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Exxon Mobil: 14,194,000 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Valero: 12,619,000 barrels', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Chevron: 9,243,000 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Motiva Enterprises (Shell): 8,942,000 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Marathon:  6,080,000 barrels\r\n', u' \xa0\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nIn January 2012, the U.S. imported a total of 119,620,000 barrels of crude oil from OPEC countries (Algeria, Angola, Ecuador, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, and Venezuela).  That works out to an average of 3.9 million barrels of crude oil per day.\r\n', u' \xa0\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nSome of these figures are way off the mark.  According to DOE figures, in January 2012 the above-listed companies imported oil from Middle Eastern countries in the following quantities:\r\n', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Valero: 12,619,000 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 BP North America: 3,161,000 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 ConocoPhillips: 1,470,000 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 ARCO (BP West Coast Products): 875,000 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Sunoco: 0 barrels', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Sinclair: 0 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Hess: 0 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Maverick: 0 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Flying J: 0 barrels ', u'\r\n\xa0 \xa0 Murphy Oil: 0 barrels\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nEven these figures are problematic, however, for a number of reasons:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 4 April 2012\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
