 extend his contract.  The notion that Robinson's coaching job was in jeopardy simply because his team was a mere three games under the break-even mark at one point in the  ", u' season is therefore rather far-fetched.  \r\n', u'\r\nSecond, no special stimulus funds were rushed to OSU by the ', u' of Education in early 2010.  Oregon, like other states, ', u' back in 2009 to receive money available through the State Fiscal Stabilization Fund (', u'), a program intended to help schools retain teachers and professors and to pay for needed maintenance and infrastructure projects.  And Oregon, like other states, decided how to allocate those funds to its various state school districts and institutions of higher learning.   (Oregon applied for ', u' from the SFSF and eventually allocated ', u' of that amount to OSU.)\r\n', u"\r\nFinally, the chronology of events disproves the claim that there was some form of linkage between stimulus funds and Robinson's March 2010 contract extension. OSU applied for SFSF funds in ", u' and as noted in a ', u' 2009 ', u' ', u', OSU had already received and spent ', u" of state fiscal stabilization funds by that date. But OSU's ", u" men's basketball season didn't even get underway until ", u" and the team's ", u" start (which was the factor supposedly putting Robinson's job in jeopardy) didn't come to pass until January 2010.  Stimulus funds that had been asked for, received, and spent well before the start of the ", u" basketball season could not possibly have been a nepotistic inducement quickly procured for the university in order to save Robinson's coaching job partway through that  season.\r\n", u"\r\nBoth OSU's athletic director and its director of news and communications have denied there is any truth to the rumor:\r\n\r\n", u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 23 March 2010\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
