lim, claims that her late father, her mother and her brother were all "connected" to Muslim Brotherhood have no factual basis to them.  That rumor was promulgated by former Republican Congresswoman Michele Bachmann of Minnesota, who in June 2012 sent a ', u' to the Deputy Inspector General at the Department of State asserting that "infomation has recently come to light that raises serious questions about Department of State policies and activities that appear to be a result of influence operations conducted by individuals and organizations associated with the Muslim Brotherhood."  Bachmann cited as proof of these nefarious "influence operations" the example that "the Department\'s Deputy Chief of Staff, Huma Abedin, has three family ', u' late father, her mother and her ', u' to Muslim Brotherhood operatives and/or organizations. Her position affords her routine access to the Secretary and to policy-making." \r\n', u'\r\nEven Bachmann\'s fellow Republican John McCain found her claims about Abedin so outrageous that he condemned them on the floor of the U.S. Senate as having "no logic, no basis and no merit":\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nLike Huma Abedin, Arif Alikhan is the American-born child of an Indian father and a Pakistani mother.  He served as Deputy Mayor of Homeland Security and Public Safety for the City of Los Angeles, as a federal prosecutor with the United States Attorneys Office in Los Angeles, and a senior adviser to Attorneys General John Ashcroft and Alberto Gonzales before being tapped by the Obama administration in 2009 to fill a position as Assistant Secretary for Policy Development at the U.S. Department of Homeland Security (DHS).  Although Alikhan has been described as a "devout Sunni" in the foreign press, he is a knowledgeable and respected expert in his field, a former Distinguished Professor of Homeland Security and Counterterrorism at the National Defense University who teaches and lectures on counter-terrorism issues for U.S. military and civilian security professionals.\r\n', u'\r\nAlikhan is no longer Assistant Secretary for Policy Development at DHS, having taken up a position as Deputy Executive Director for Homeland Security, Law Enforcement, and Fire/EMS with Los Angeles World Airports (LAWA) in 2011, where he oversees police, civilian security, and fire and emergency medical services at three Los Angeles-area airports (Los Angeles International, Ontario International, and Van Nuys).  \r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 1 February 2015\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
