@@@ [u" \xa0 Georgia held a hearing to determine Barack Obama's eligibility to appear on that state's ballot as a presidential candidate.\r\n", u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u" \xa0 In January 2012, attorney Orly Taitz represented plaintiffs who had filed a complaint with Georgia Secretary of State Brian Kemp, maintaining that Barack Obama should not appear on that state's ballot as a presidential candidate as he is not  eligible to hold the office of President of the United States.  Unlike previous attempts to have Barack Obama declared ineligible for the presidency, in this case the plaintiffs did not claim that Barack Obama was ineligible because he was born outside the United States; instead, they stipulated he was born in Hawaii but argued that an 1875 Supreme Court ruling (", u') defined "natural born citizens" as people born in the United States to parents who are both U.S. citizens, and since Barack Obama\'s father was not an American citizen, Barack Obama himself does not qualify for that status, which is a constitutional requirement for the presidency:\r\n\r\n', u"\r\n\r\nSince Georgia state law stipulates that if a candidate's qualifications are challenged the Secretary of State must request a hearing on the matter before an administrative law judge, the issue was referred to Georgia Deputy Chief Judge Michael Malihi in the Office of State Administrative Hearings.  Judge Malihi denied a motion by Barack Obama's attorneys to dismiss the complaint and scheduled a hearing for ", u' 2012.\r\n', u"\r\nThe plaintiffs presented their case at that hearing, which both Barack Obama and his legal team declined to attend.  (Although Judge Malihi had denied a motion to quash a subpoena for President Obama to appear at the hearing, Obama's legal team argued that no president should be compelled to attend a court hearing, and the President instead spent the day unveiling new energy initiatives In ", u'\r\n', u"\r\nJudge Malihi offered no verdict regarding the case, as his role was only to gather facts and make a recommendation; the official decision on whether Barack Obama will be listed on the Georgia ballot rests with Secretary of State Brian Kemp.  However, in Judge Malihi's ", u' issued on ', u' 2012, he concluded that "President Barack Obama was born in the United States. Therefore, he became a  citizen at birth and is a natural born citizen. Accordingly, President Barack Obama is eligible as a candidate for the presidential primary election":\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nOn 7 February 2012, Georgia Secretary of State Brian Kemp issued a final ', u" stating that Barack Obama was qualified to remain on Georgia's ballot as a presidential candidate:\r\n\r\n", u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 11 February 2012\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
