r to be the villain in this story, neither side may be correct in claiming the high ground since both CandySwipe and Candy Crush Saga are notably similar to other games dating from the mid-1990s, and what is being disputed is merely the name that each side is using for their version of the game rather than a claim to the original idea itself (i.e., this is a tussle over trademarks, not copyright):\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' also reported an attempt by developers to challenge King\'s trademark maneuvering by creating "as many games with the word candy in them as possible":\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThe International Game Developers Association (IGDA) has also ', u' in on the issue, describing King\'s trademark efforts as "overreaching" and "predatory":\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 17 April 2014\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
