@@@ [u' \xa0 The U.S. government has agreed to allow China to exercise "eminent domain" as collateral for American debt. \r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 The large amount of U.S. debt held by foreign countries such as China has long concerned many Americans, and especially so with the current climate of economic turmoil.  As the ', u' noted:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nLikewise, as ', u' news reported, some Chinese officals have opined that China should ask the U.S. for some economic guarantees as a prerequisite for additional purchases of ', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nBut that\'s as far as the truth of the item cited in the example block above goes.  The notion that the U.S. has agreed to guarantee its foreign debt by granting China permission to enact "eminent domain" and "physically take land, buildings, factories, perhaps even entire cities" from the U.S. isn\'t even a sensible claim.  \r\n', u'\r\nThe concept of "eminent domain" in the United States refers to the right of the government to seize private property for public use ', u'.  (The Fifth Amendment to the Constitution ', u' that "private property [shall not] be taken for public use, without just compensation.")  Thus the idea of enacting eminent domain as a form of debt repayment or guarantee isn\'t logical: It\'s akin to a debtor\'s offering to settle a $5,000 debt by agreeing to sell his creditor $5,000 worth of jewelry for ', u" the end of the day, the debtor hasn't given up anything, and his creditor still hasn't collected anything on his original loan amount.\r\n", u'\r\nMoreover, Executive Order ', u' ("Protecting the Property Rights of the American People") states that the the federal government must limit its use of the taking of private property "to situations in which the taking is for public use, with just compensation" and "not merely for the purpose of advancing the economic interest of private parties to be given ownership or use of the property taken."\r\n', u'\r\nAside from functional arguments, the common sense test applies: If the U.S. government had actually guaranteed, in writing, that China could seize private property within the U.S. to satisfy the financial obligations of the ', u' that information would be the biggest new story of the day.  So who is reporting this news?  Not any legitimate news outlet \u2014 the story appears only in the blog of former radio host ', u' (who has previously presented fictitious tales of politically outrageous subjects as actual occurrences, such as proffering fake ', u' coins as proof of a secret conspiracy to merge the U.S., Mexico, and Canada into a single entity) and in hundreds of identical Internet replications.\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 8 March 2009\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
