@@@ [u" \xa0 The domain GeorgeWBush.com hosts the legitimate web site of President Bush's 2004 re-election campaign.\r\n", u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 Many netizens who received the e-mail exhortation quoted above out of the blue in ', u' wondered it if was legitimate.  The Internet is rife with \r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nfraud, after all, and setting up imitation web sites using domain names similar to those of legitimate organizations is a common scam technique.  (If President ', u" Smith's official campaign site were found at johnqsmith.com, for example, scammers would still have plenty of room to reel in victims by setting up shop at johnsmith.com, jqsmith.com. jqs.com, presidentsmith.com, etc.).\r\n", u"\r\nThere's no fraud here, however.  The web site mentioned in this message \u2014 www.GeorgeWBush.com ", u" indeed the legitimate web site of President Bush's ", u' campaign organization, ', u'  On ', u' 2003, President Bush took his first formal step towards running for ', u' by filing with the Federal Election Commission, a step which established ', u' as the official campaign organization and allowed it to begin raising money for the upcoming campaign.  Ari Fleischer, the President\'s spokesperson, said at the time of the filing that a letter to potential contributors would go out "very shortly," and the message quoted above appears to be the ', u' of that letter.  ', u" disclaimed reports that the President's ", u' campaign hopes to double the record-breaking ', u' in contributions received during the 2000 campaign, but he noted that they do expect to exceed the previous amount.\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 19 August 2007 \r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\xa0\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n'] @@@
