@@@ [u' \xa0 New U.S. dollar coins were designed with the motto "In God We Trust" omitted.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0  In 2007 the U.S. Mint began the release of a series of coins similar in concept to the ', u' Program launched in 1999.  This new series, the ', u' Program, features dollar coins identical in size, color, and composition to the \r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nearlier ', u' dollar, each one bearing the likeness of a former ', u' on the obverse (front) and a representation of the ', u' on the reverse (back).  The ', u' coins will be released in  ', u" of four per year (in order corresponding to the presidents' terms of office) beginning in February 2007.\r\n", u'\r\nJust as the first ', u' coins rolled out of the Mint in early 2007, ', u' began to circulate spreading the erroneous assertion that the new dollar coins did not include the phrase "In God We Trust" in their design.  In fact, the Presidential ', u' neither omitted the phrase "In God We Trust" nor demonstrated a plot to "phase God out of America."  As specified by Presidential ', u' Act of 2005, in order to allow for "larger and more dramatic artwork" on the coins\' faces, the new ', u' coins incorporated a few design features not found on other current ', u' one of which is that elements typically displayed on either the obverse or reverse of  ', u' year of minting, the mint mark, the motto from the Great Seal of the United States ', u' Unum"), and the current national motto of the United States ("In God We ', u' instead included as edge-incused inscriptions.  That is, all of these elements appeared on the edges of the new dollar coins rather than on their fronts or backs:\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\nThe following photograph shows how the national motto is stamped as an edge-incused inscription on a dollar coin blank: \r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u"\r\n(Small quantities of the George Washington and John Adams presidential dollars were discovered to be missing their edge inscriptions shortly after the initial release of those coins, but those examples were the result of minting errors and were not reflective of the new dollars' intended standard appearance.  The stamping of the faces and the adding of the edge inscriptions are separate steps in the minting process and involve the use of different machinery.)  \r\n", u'\r\nWith the passage of the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2008, Congress reversed its previous specifications and instructed the ', u' to move the "In God We Trust" motto from the edge to the front or back of the presidential ', u' "as soon as is practicable."  Beginning with the first Presidential ', u' issued in 2009 (which bore the likeness of the ninth ', u' William Henry Harrison), the motto was repositioned to the bottom left-hand portion of the obverse:\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\nOne traditional feature that ', u' been left off the new dollar coins is the appearance of the word "Liberty."  The ', u' explained the change by noting that "each coin represents this important value by depicting the Statue of Liberty on the reverse":\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 1 January 2013\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
@@@ [u' \xa0 Schools in the UK no longer teach about the Holocaust for fear of offending Muslim students. \r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u" \xa0 This piece about UK schools reportedly dropping the subject of the Holocaust from  history claases began circulating via e-mail in mid-April 2007. Its central claim, that schools in Britain no longer teach about the Holocaust for fear of offending Muslim students, isn't on the money: Even news ", u' that bore headlines\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nsuch as "Teachers drop the Holocaust to avoid offending Muslims" only cited a single example of ', u' history department in a northern UK school that did that (and for reasons other than avoiding "offending Muslims"). In all the rest of the country\'s schools, information about the Holocaust was still being imparted to students.\r\n', u'\r\nThose news articles were a response to the ', u" release of the Historical Association's report titled ", u' (an overview of its objectives can be found ', u' and the full report ', u"), a study funded by the UK's Department for Education and Skills to examine how educators in Britain were teaching sensitive and/or controversial aspects of history and to highlight what approaches had worked among those that had been tried. \r\n", u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\nOne history department looked at by the fact-finders was found to have cut information about the Holocaust from its lessons due to worries that Muslim pupils might express anti-Semitic reactions. Said the report: "For example, a history department in a northern city recently avoided \r\nselecting the Holocaust as a topic for GCSE coursework for fear of confronting anti-Semitic sentiment and Holocaust denial among some Muslim pupils."\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\nFrom this single example of one UK school was spun the claim that every school in that country had stopped teaching about the Holocaust for fear of offending Muslim students. In fact, the education department\'s plan was the opposite: to ensure that the Holocaust was taught everywhere. A spokesman for the Department of Education and Skills (DES) maintained that "The ', u'  report on citizenship [a different report authored by Sir Keith Ajegbo and released in January 2007] said key British historical events must be taught" and that while "the national curriculum is a broad framework and there is scope for schools to make their own decisions,  teaching elements including the Holocaust and key British events will be compulsory."\r\n', u'\r\nAccording to a DES spokesman, "Teaching of the Holocaust is already compulsory in schools at Key ', u' ', u' and it will remain so in the new KS3 curriculum from September 2008."  Schools in Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland have different guidelines and curriculums; in those parts of the UK, according to the BBC, "Holocaust teaching is not compulsory but schools may teach it if they wish, and this has not changed recently."\r\n', u'\r\nThe bottom line to all this fuss?  Schools in the UK are indeed teaching about the Holocaust, something British journalists seemed to downplay in their rush to report that one department in one city was not. The ', u' call to arms cited above was likely the result of a misreading of already badly-presented news articles.\r\n', u'\r\nSeveral months after the original of this item first appeared, someone mistook (or deliberately confused) the abbreviation "UK" with the University of Kentucky and changed the central claim to be "the University of Kentucky had removed The Holocaust from its school curriculum." The University of Kentucky issued a ', u' on 8 November 2007 to correct this misinformation:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u' \xa0 Versions of this item circulated in early 2008 included the following preface:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nBarbara "scrambled regs" Mikkelson\r\n', u' \r\n', u' \xa0 14 May 2015\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
@@@ [u' \xa0 Franchised postal center outlets may charge more than official postal service rates for mailing items.\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 One business model that has proved quite successful over the last several decades is that of the private postal center.    Through both independent stores and chain/franchise outlets (such as ', u' and ', u'), these businesses, although not affiliated with the United States Postal Service (USPS), provide many of the same services as ', u' offices: they rent mailboxes (similar to post office boxes), sell postage stamps, vend mailing supplies, and package and ship items via ', u'  These businesses appeal to customers with a variety of needs: those who want the safety and security of receiving mail at sites other than their residence addresses, those who need someone to accept delivery of parcels and signature-required items on their behalf during hours when they would not be home to do so themselves, those who travel and move \r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\naround  frequently and need mail services at multiple locations, and those who live in areas where the local ', u' office is not conveniently located for them.\r\n', u'\r\nThese businesses also typically provide a variety of services not generally offered at ', u' offices, such as the shipment of items via other delivery services (e.g., UPS, FedEx), fax services, copy/print services, passport photos, money transfers, key cutting, and notary services.  (The United Parcel Service offers many of these same services at its own branded ', u' which are franchised by the Mail ', u' chain, a subsidiary of UPS.)\r\n', u'\r\nAll of this convenience comes with a price, however.  Customers who buy postage stamps at private postal outlets will typically pay a ', u' over the face value, and those who use such outlets to ship items via USPS, UPS, or FedEx generally pay a premium over what they would be charged if they dealt with those entities directly.  Most regular customers consider those additional fees to be worthwhile ', u' for the convenience factor, but many folks who only occasionally use such services have been surprised (and disgruntled) to learn that they have been paying surcharges above the standard shipping rates.  As a December 2009 ', u' article on the subject observed:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThe article also noted that:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nThe situation is somewhat more complicated in Canada, where customers can choose between outlets of private postal chains such as ', u', ', u' or ', u' and official Canada Post ', u' outlets.  The example quoted at the head of this article purportedly recounts the experience of a disgruntled customer who utilized one of the latter, a Canada Post franchise location (in a drug store), and was not only charged over 50% more than the cost of mailing an identical package at a Canada Post post office but was also supposedly told by a Canada Post representative that Canada Post franchises "may charge extra fees as a convenience to their customers" at their discretion.\r\n', u'\r\nThe substance of this ', u' seems to be inaccurate: the packages mailed by the customer (although they may have contained similar items) apparently were not identical; the second one was packaged in a way that made it slightly bulkier than the first, and it therefore did not fit through the smaller mail slot that would have qualified it for a lower postage rate.\r\n', u"\r\nCanada Post's initial response to this matter acknowledged that inaccurate information was provided by a Canada Post representative to the customer in question but affirmed that Canada Post franchise outlets are not authorized to charge customers more than the published Canada Post rates:\r\n\r\n", u'\r\n\r\nCanada Post later ', u'disclaimed the purported reply as a hoax, claiming that they had no employee named "Veronika Strofski."\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 23 February 2010\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
