@@@ [u' \xa0 American Atheists are opposing the incorporation of a steel-beam cross found in the World Trade Center rubble into a ', u' memorial and museum. \r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 ', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 The discovery of a 17-foot steel-beam ', u' in the rubble of the World Trade Center towers two days after the 2001 terrorist attacks on America provided a tangible symbol of comfort and faith to many of those horrified by the events of ', u'  Some of those who had access to \r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nthe WTC site at that time made pilgrimages to pray before the cross and leave behind written messages such as "God Bless Our Fallen Brothers."  A few weeks later the cross (since dubbed the "Ground Zero Cross") was hoisted atop a ', u' mound of debris on what was formerly a pedestrian walkway so that it could be viewed by a wider audience, and a religious service was held, during which the ', u' Jordan sprinkled the cross with holy water and declared: "Behold the glory of the cross at ground zero. This is our symbol of hope, our symbol of faith, our symbol of healing."   Countless other ceremonies and prayer vigils were held at the site of WTC cross in the weeks and months that followed.   Two years later, the cross remains in place along Church Street on the eastern border of the ', u' WTC site.\r\n', u'\r\nAfter the unearthing of the steel-beam cross from the WTC rubble, a number of groups supported the idea of incorporating the steel cross into the design of a future ', u' memorial display at the site.   The ', u' organization opposed such plans for reasons ', u' by their president, Ellen Johnson, at least as far back as ', u':\r\n\r\n', u"\r\n\r\nMs. Johnson reiterated American Atheists' position in the ", u' 2003 edition of ', u':\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\nPlans called for the 17-foot World Trade Center crossbeam to be on display at the museum portion of the ', u' when that facility opened.  In 2011 American Atheists filed a lawsuit to prevent that display, contending that the museum would be violating the \r\n\r\n', u"\r\n\r\nConstitution's establishment clause and ", u' state civil-rights law by exhibiting a religious symbol.  In August 2012, the National ', u' ', u" filed court papers seeking a dismissal of the lawsuit on the grounds that the museum is operated by an independent non-profit corporation and its decisions about what to display are therefore not state actions subject to constitutional protection, that the crossbeam is being exhibited as a relic of the 9/11 attacks and not as a religious symbol, and that the museum's merely displaying an object with religious significance does not amount to an endorsement or promotion of a particular religion.\r\n", u'\r\nIn July 2014, a the three-judge panel of the Second Circuit Court denied the American Atheists\' appeal and ruled that the Ground Zero cross could remain in the museum,  holding that it served more as a "genuine historical artifact" than as a symbol of Christianity:\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u' \xa0 10 January 2015\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n', u'\r\n'] @@@
